{{about|the British historian|the American actor|Geoffrey Cantor (actor)}} '''Geoffrey N. Cantor''' (born 1943) is [[Emeritus]] [[Professor]] of the [[History and Philosophy of Science]] at the [[University of Leeds]] and Honorary Senior Research Associate at [[UCL Department of Science and Technology Studies]] at [[University College London]]. He has written about [[Michael Faraday]], the [[wave theory of light]] and the responses of the [[Quaker]] and [[Jewish]] religions to science.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.rigb.org/contentControl?action=displayContent&id=00000001287 |publisher=The Royal Institution of Great Britain |title=Prof Geoffrey Cantor |year=2005 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625230017/http://www.rigb.org/contentControl?action=displayContent&id=00000001287 |archivedate=2010-06-25 |df= }}</ref> With [[John Hedley Brooke]] he delivered the 1995–1996 [[Gifford Lectures|Gifford Lecture]] at the [[University of Glasgow]], which were subsequently published as ''Reconstructing Nature: The Engagement of Science and Religion'' in 1998.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.giffordlectures.org/Author.asp?AuthorID=232 |title=Geoffrey Cantor |publisher=Gifford Lectures Online |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308152751/http://www.giffordlectures.org/Author.asp?AuthorID=232 |archivedate=2008-03-08 |df= }}</ref> He contributed to the [[SciPer]] project, which researches the popularization of science in the [[periodical]]s of the 19th century, such as the [[Boy's Own Paper]] and [[Punch (magazine)|Punch]], and has lectured upon this subject at the [[Royal Institution]] in 2005.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.rigb.org/contentControl?action=displayEvent&id=121 |publisher=The Royal Institution of Great Britain |title=Punchlines: from wit to wisdom |date=25 January 2005 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612053220/http://www.rigb.org/contentControl?action=displayEvent&id=121 |archivedate=2011-06-12 |df= }}</ref>
