[[File:JuanGrijalvaCuellar.jpg|thumb|right|Juan de Grijalva]] '''Juan de Grijalva''' ({{IPA-es|xwan de ɣɾiˈxalβa|lang}}; born around 1489 in [[Cuéllar]], [[Crown of Castille]] - 21 January 1527 in [[Nicaragua]]) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] [[conquistador]], and relation of [[Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar|Diego Velázquez]].<ref name=Diaz>Diaz, B., 1963, The Conquest of New Spain, London: Penguin Books, {{ISBN|0140441239}}</ref>{{rp|27}} He went to [[Hispaniola]] in 1508 and to [[Cuba]] in 1511. He was one of the early explorers of the Mexican coastline.
==1518 expedition== In 1518 Grijalva was one of the earliest to explore the shores of [[Mexico]]. According to [[Hernán Cortés]], 170 people went with him, but according to [[Peter Martyr d'Anghiera|Pedro Mártir]], there were 300 people. The [[Maritime pilot|main pilot]] was [[Antón de Alaminos]], the other pilots were Juan Álvarez (also known as ''el Manquillo''), [[Pedro Camacho de Triana]], and Grijalva. Other members included [[Francisco de Montejo]], [[Pedro de Alvarado]], [[Juan Díaz (Spanish conquistador)|Juan Díaz]], [[Francisco Peñalosa]], Alonso de Ávila,<ref name=Diaz/>{{rp|50}} Alonso Hernández, [[Julianillo]], [[Melchorejo]], and [[Antonio Villafaña]]. They embarked from the port of [[Matanzas]], [[Cuba]], with four ships in April 1518.
[[File:Expedición de Girjalva 1518.svg|thumb|300px|Juan de Grijalva, expedition in 1518. Discovery by the Europeans of the Grijalva River.]] After rounding the [[Cape San Antonio, Cuba|Guaniguanico]] in Cuba, Grijalva sailed along the Mexican coast, discovered [[Cozumel]], and arrived on 1 May at the [[Tabasco]] region in southern Mexico. The [[Grijalva River|Río Grijalva]] in Mexico was named after him. He was also the first Spaniard to encounter [[Moctezuma II]]'s delegation. One of the natives joined them, being baptized as Francisco, and became an interpreter on Cortes' expedition. [[Bernal Díaz del Castillo]] wrote about the travels of Juan de Grijalva in his book.<ref name=Diaz/>{{rp|27-43,82}}
In 1518 [[Hernan Cortes]] stayed at Juan's home in [[Trinidad, Cuba]], at the start of his Mexican expedition. He recruited men there, including the five Alvarado brothers.<ref name=Diaz/>{{rp|49-50}}
He was killed by natives in [[Honduras]] on 21 January 1527.
