'''Maria Celina Dzielska''' (née '''Dąbrowska''', September 18, 1942 – July 30, 2018) was a Polish classical [[philology|philologist]], historian, translator, biographer of [[Hypatia]], and political activist. She was a Professor of Ancient Roman History at [[Jagiellonian University]].{{r|fronda}}

==Education and career==
Dzielska was born in [[Krakow]]. She has degrees in history from the Jagiellonian University and in classical philology from the [[University of Łódź]], completing her Ph.D. in 1972 and her [[habilitation]] in 1984. She was promoted to full professor at Jagiellonian University in 1996.{{r|fronda}}

==Activism==
Dzielska married [[Mirosław Dzielski]], a leader of the 1980s anti-communist movement in Poland, and campaigned against communism with him.{{r|fronda}}

==Recognition==
Dzielska became a member of the [[Polish Academy of Sciences]] and the [[Polish Academy of Learning]].{{r|fronda}}
At her death, she was given a [[state funeral]] at which Polish president [[Andrzej Duda]] gave her the [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]].{{r|deon}}

==Select publications==
*''Apollonius of Tyana in Legend and History'' (translated into English by Piotr Pieńkowski; Rome: l'Erma di Bretschneider, 1986){{r|atlh}}
*''Hypatia of Alexandria'' (translated into English by F. Lyra; Cambridge: Harvard Univ. Press, 1995){{r|hyp}}
*''Divine Men and Women in the History and Society of Late Hellenism'' (edited with Kamilla Twardowska, Jagiellonian University Press, 2013){{r|dmw}}

