'''''Oxford University Studies in the Enlightenment''''' is a [[monographic series]] which has been published since 1955.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.voltaire.ox.ac.uk/www_vf/ose/es_default.ssi|title=Voltaire Foundation: Oxford University Studies in the Enlightenment|website=www.voltaire.ox.ac.uk|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref> Originally edited by [[Theodore Besterman]],<ref name=worldcat>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/studies-on-voltaire-and-the-eighteenth-century/oclc/1766759&referer=brief_results |title=Worldcat record |publisher=Worldcat.org |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref><ref name="oxdnb">
{{cite book
 |last=Barber
 |first=Giles
 |title=Besterman, Theodore Deodatus Nathaniel (1904–1976)
 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]
 |year=2004|volume=[[Dictionary of National Biography]]
 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37189
 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> the series now comprises more than 550 books - edited volumes and monographs, in either English or French - on diverse topics related to the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] or the eighteenth century. The current General Editor is [[Gregory S. Brown]], who took up the post at the start of 2016.<ref name=":0" />

== Name ==
Previously the series was called '''''Studies on Voltaire and the Eighteenth Century''''' ('''SVEC'''). In 2013, the name was changed to reflect the publication's global and interdisciplinary scope, which includes the [[Age of Enlightenment]] in the long Eighteenth Century and growing scholarly move to see the Enlightenment as a movement with worldwide impact and implications.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dow|first1=Gillian|title=Translation, Cross-Channel Exchanges and the Novel in the Long Eighteenth Century|journal=Literature Compass|date=November 2014|volume=11|issue=11|pages=691–702|doi=10.1111/lic3.12183}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://voltairefoundation.wordpress.com/2014/01/13/oxford-university-studies-in-the-enlightenment-whats-in-a-name/ |title=Oxford University Studies in the Enlightenment – what’s in a name? |publisher=Voltaire Foundation  |date=2014-01-13 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> Currently it is published by the [[Voltaire Foundation]], an academic department in the Division of Humanities of the University of Oxford. Volumes prior to 1970 were published by the [[Institut et Musée Voltaire]] in [[Geneva]].<ref name=worldcat />. In September 2017, the Voltaire Foundation announced a partnership with [[Liverpool University Press]], which will take on responsibility for printing, warehousing, marketing and distribution of the series in 2018.

== Topics ==
The series publishes one book per month. Topics include history, literature and comparative studies, cultural studies, philosophy, the history of the book, theatre, arts and visual studies, and gender studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://163.1.91.91/_svec_index/soi_IdxPage.lasso|title=SVEC Online Index|website=163.1.91.91|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref> Several of its books have won awards, such as the Society for the History of Natural History's [[Society for the History of Natural History#Medals and prizes|Thackray Medal]] for ''Jean-Jacques Rousseau and botany: the salutary science'' (Alexandra Cook),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shnh.org.uk/awards-honours-medals/john-thackray-medal/|title=The John Thackray Medal - Society for the History of Natural History|website=Society for the History of Natural History|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sydney.edu.au/intellectual-history/people/collaborators.shtml |title=Australian and international collaborators|publisher=The University of Sydney|work=Sydney.edu.au |date=2014-02-27 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> and the Prix Marianne Roland Michel for ''The Profession of sculpture in the Paris 'Académie''' (Tomas Macsotay).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mariannerolandmichel.fr/prix.html#livres |title=Le Prix Marianne Roland Michel |work=Mariannerolandmichel.fr | publisher=Fondation Marianne & Roland Michel|date= |accessdate=2014-04-27|language=French}}</ref>

