'''Soledad Acosta Kemble''' (5 May 1833 – 17 March 1913)<ref name="lablaa">{{cite book |last1=Samper |first1=Santiago |editor1-first=Jorge Orlando |editor1-last=Melo González |title=Gran Enciclopedia de Colombia del Círculo de Lectores, tomo de biografías |trans-title=Great Encyclopaedia of Colombia, Volume of Biographies |url=http://www.banrepcultural.org/blaavirtual/biografias/acossole.htm |accessdate=1 November 2010 |publisher=[[Luis Ángel Arango Library]] |location=Bogotá |language=Spanish }}</ref> was a [[Colombian people|Colombian]] writer and journalist. A sophisticated, well-travelled, and social woman, she received a much higher and better rounded education than most women of her time and country, and enjoyed a high standing in society, not only for her family background, but for her own literary endeavours. She collaborated in various newspapers including ''[[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]]'', ''El Deber'', and ''Revista Americana'', among other periodicals. Using her writings, she was a feminist well ahead of her time, she lobbied for equal education for women, and wrote on various topics pertaining to female participation in society and family, encouraging others to become proactive in the workforce and in the restoration of society.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pratt |first1=Mary Louise |authorlink1=Mary Louise Pratt |editor1-first=Doris |editor1-last=Meyer |title=Rereading the Spanish American essay: translations of 19th and 20th century women's essays |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AK-F_apKm1IC |accessdate=1 November 2010 |edition= |series=The Texas Pan American series |year=1995 |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]] |location=Austin |isbn=978-0-292-75182-8 |oclc=32015586|pages=67–76 |chapter=Soledad Acosta de Samper |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=AK-F_apKm1IC&pg=PA67}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Janet |last2=Humphrey |first2=Ted |authorlink2=Ted Humphrey |title=Nineteenth-century nation building and the Latin American intellectual tradition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_aDh_eVx8FgC |accessdate=1 November 2010 |year=2007 |publisher=[[Hackett Publishing]] |location=Indianapolis |isbn=978-0-87220-837-7 |oclc=72161781|chapter=Soledad Acosta de Samper |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=_aDh_eVx8FgC&pg=PA268}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Bassnett |first1=Susan |authorlink1=Susan Bassnett |title=Knives and angels: women writers in Latin America |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GwujbDcmcvMC |accessdate=1 November 2010 |year=1990 |publisher=[[Zed Books]] |location=London |isbn=9780862328757 |pages=132–137 |chapter=9. One hundred years of unread writing: Soledad Acosta, Elisa Mujica and Marvel Moreno |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=GwujbDcmcvMC&pg=PA132}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Soledad was born on 5 May 1833,<ref name="lablaa"/> to [[Tomás Joaquín de Acosta y Pérez de Guzmán]], and Caroline Kemble Rowe in [[Bogotá]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | last=Martin|first=Crista|title=Acosta de Samper, Soledad|pages=31–32|volume=1|editor=Commire, Anne|encyclopedia=[[Women in World History|Women in World History: A biographical encyclopedia]]|year=1999|publisher=Yorkin Publications, Gale Group|location=Waterford, CT|ISBN=0787640808}}</ref> Her father was a native of [[Guaduas]] the son of Spanish immigrants, he was a scientist, diplomat and general; her mother, a native of [[Kingston, Jamaica]], was the daughter of Gideon Kemble, an American Scotsman and Collector of the Port of Kingston, and his wife Tomasa (née Rowe).<ref>Due to [[Phonetic transcription]], Mrs. Kemble's maiden name has been changed to "Rou" in many Spanish language sources.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Stout |first1=Kemble |title=Genealogy of the Kemble (Kimble) family in America |type=[[Genealogy book]] |year=1992 |location=Pullman, WA |oclc=27175549|page=356}}</ref> On 5 May 1855 she married [[José María Samper Agudelo]], a renowned writer and journalist, and together they had four daughters, [[Bertilda Samper Acosta|Bertilda]], who become a nun, and took up poetry like her parents, Carolina (b. 1857) and María Josefa (b. 1860), both of whom died in 1872 during a [[smallpox]] outbreak in Bogotá, and Blanca Leonor (b. 1862).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Acosta |first1=Soledad |editor1-first=Montserrat |editor1-last=Ordóñez Vila |others=Chronology by María Victoria González |title=Novelas y cuadros de la vida suramericana |trans-title=Novels and Portraits of South American Life |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VJCcINGg5IQC |accessdate=31 October 2010 |date=August 2004 |publisher= |location=Bogotá |language=Spanish |isbn=978-958-683-706-4 |oclc=254691569|pages=405–406 |trans-chapter=Chronology |chapter=Cronología |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=VJCcINGg5IQC&pg=PA403 }}</ref>

